		<h1>PYRAMIDS</h1>
		<p>
			<strong>The Pyramids of Egypt</strong>, iconic symbols of ancient Egyptian civilization, are among the most famous architectural wonders in the world. Located on the Giza Plateau near Cairo, the three Great Pyramids—Khufu (also known as the Great Pyramid), Khafre, and Menkaure—stand as enduring testaments to the engineering and artistic prowess of the ancient Egyptians. The Great Pyramid of Khufu, the largest and oldest of the three, is the last remaining wonder of the ancient world and was originally built as a tomb for the Pharaoh Khufu around 2600 BCE. These monumental structures were constructed with massive limestone and granite blocks, precisely aligned to the cardinal points of the compass, reflecting advanced knowledge of astronomy and mathematics. Surrounding the pyramids are smaller pyramids, temples, and the famous Great Sphinx, a limestone statue with a lion's body and a human head, believed to represent Pharaoh Khafre. The pyramids are not only marvels of construction but also repositories of ancient religious and cultural practices, as they were designed to honor the pharaohs and ensure their safe journey to the afterlife. Today, the Pyramids of Giza attract millions of tourists annually and continue to captivate archaeologists and historians, offering a glimpse into the grandeur and mysteries of ancient Egypt.
		</p>
